Mapping Detroit's Housing Inequities

Christy Choi, Ellis Dyke, Atika Nusrat

For over a century, Detroit's housing landscape has reflected America's most entrenched racial and economic divides. Inspired by research from the Harms Report for the Detroit Reparations Task Force published by the University of Michigan, this project reveals how discriminatory policies systematically shaped the city's neighborhoods.

Each visualization builds upon the report's documentation of:

  • Population shifts following racist housing policies (p. 7-9)
  • Home value disparities tied to redlining (p. 4, 7-8)
  • The disproportionate impact of urban renewal on Black communities (p. 14-15)

By combining the report's historical analysis with publicly available data, including census data, we reveal how racism continues to influence who can build wealth through homeownership in Detroit today. Our interactive visualizer explores five pillars of Detroit’s housing inequity:

  • Population Trends Over Time: Track white flight and Black population growth amid systemic segregation.
  • Racial Proportions by Location: Compare Detroit’s Black majority with persistently white suburbs.
  • Homeownership by Race: Uncover how exclusion shaped ownership "gains."
  • Median Home Values by Race: See how redlining depressed Black neighborhood wealth.
  • HOLC Redlining and DLBA Sales & Re-Occupancy: Explore how federal policy graded Black areas as "hazardous" and assess post-foreclosure recovery efforts

Explore these tools to see how racist policies engineered Detroit’s racial and spatial divides—and why repair demands systemic change.

1. Population Trends Over Time by Race and Location

This visualization tracks demographic shifts in Detroit and its suburbs from 1940 to 2020. The data reveals the stark consequences of white flight, a phenomenon accelerated by federal redlining, racially restrictive covenants, and violent resistance to integration. As white residents moved to suburbs (aided by GI Bill benefits denied to Black veterans), Detroit’s Black population grew—yet became concentrated in under-resourced urban neighborhoods. By 2010, the city had lost over 50% of its peak 1950 population, with Black residents bearing the brunt of disinvestment.

2. Proportion of Black and White Populations Over Time by Location

Compare racial proportions in Detroit versus its suburbs to see how segregation hardened over the 20th century. In 1940, Detroit was 90% white; by 2010, it was 83% Black. Meanwhile, suburbs like Dearborn and Grosse Pointe remained overwhelmingly white due to exclusionary policies (e.g., "sundown town" ordinances). This divide reflects deliberate choices: federal redlining maps (see HOLC Grades below) labeled Black neighborhoods "hazardous," while suburbs used restrictive covenants to block Black homeownership.

3. Demographics and Homeownership by Race in Detroit

This dual-axis visualization exposes two brutal truths:

  • Population Collapse: Detroit’s white population plummeted from 1.47 million (1940) to way below 100,000 (2010) as Black residents became the majority.
  • Homeownership "Gaps":
    • In 1940, only 3% of homeowners were Black (vs. 97% white) due to racist covenants and violence (e.g., the 1925 Ossian Sweet case).
    • By 2010, Black homeownership rose to 77%—but only because white flight and displacement left Black residents in a hollowed-out city. True equity was never achieved.

4. Trends in Median Home Values by Black Population

This graph illustrates the racial wealth gap fueled by redlining and urban renewal. From 1950–1960, homes in majority-Black census tracts lost value relative to white areas, as disinvestment and predatory practices (e.g., blockbusting) destabilized Black neighborhoods. The destruction of Black Bottom and Paradise Valley for highways and "renewal" projects (displacing 8,231 families, 95% Black) further depressed property values—a legacy visible in today’s $66,700 median Detroit home value versus $223,800 in the metro area.

5. HOLC Redlining and DLBA Sales & Re-Occupancy (2014–2024)

The federal Home Owners’ Loan Corporation (HOLC) graded neighborhoods by perceived risk, with Black areas (like Black Bottom) marked red/"hazardous"—denying residents loans and insurance. This map codified segregation, as white suburbs (green/"best") received investment while Black neighborhoods were starved of resources. The infamous Birwood Wall, built to separate Black and white communities, stands as a physical relic of this policy.

This animated map tracks properties sold by the Detroit Land Bank Authority, a response to the foreclosure crisis that disproportionately stripped Black homeowners of equity. After the 2008 recession, predatory lending and inflated property taxes (63,000 homes overtaxed by $600M) led to mass foreclosures, with outsiders buying homes at auction while long-time residents were displaced. The DLBA’s mixed record—some homes reoccupied, others left vacant—highlights ongoing struggles to reverse decades of harm.

Key Takeaway

These visuals collectively show how racist policies engineered segregation, extracted Black wealth, and left Detroit’s housing system fractured. Repair requires confronting this history—from redlining to foreclosure—with reparative justice.
